What is Frozen String Literal in Ruby?

In Ruby, strings are mutable by default:

str = "hello"
str << " world"
# => "hello world"


But when you use:

# frozen_string_literal: true


at the top of a Ruby file, all string literals in that file become immutable (frozen).

ğŸ”¹ What does â€œfrozenâ€ mean?

A frozen object cannot be modified.

Example:

# frozen_string_literal: true

str = "hello"
str << " world"
# => raises FrozenError


Ruby will raise:

FrozenError: can't modify frozen String

ğŸ”¹ Why was this introduced?

Mainly for:

1ï¸âƒ£ Performance improvement

Without freezing:

100.times { "hello" }


Ruby creates 100 different string objects.

With frozen string literal enabled, Ruby can reuse the same object, reducing memory allocation.

2ï¸âƒ£ Memory optimization

Especially useful in large apps (like Rails apps), where many identical string literals exist.

ğŸ”¹ Before vs After Example

Without freezing:

"hello".object_id == "hello".object_id
# => false


With # frozen_string_literal: true:

"hello".object_id == "hello".object_id
# => true


Same object reused âœ”ï¸

ğŸ”¹ Can we freeze manually?

Yes:

str = "hello".freeze


But the magic comment freezes all string literals in that file automatically.

ğŸ”¹ When was this added?

It was introduced in Ruby 2.3 and became common practice in modern Ruby projects.

ğŸ”¹ Interview-Ready Answer (Short Version)

You can say:

Yes. In Ruby, strings are mutable by default. Using # frozen_string_literal: true at the top of a file makes all string literals immutable. This improves performance and reduces memory usage because Ruby reuses the same string object instead of creating new ones. It also prevents accidental modification of literals.